01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:02.000
It's pretty fast.

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:10.000
Oh, this is a, this is also, I should mention, this is a Shiny app that's running on a different server.

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:15.000
So it's not on this laptop.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:24.000
You can search for, you can do all the same stuff, and it's still pretty fast.

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:29.000
And then for fun, we can go to the 1 million row table.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:35.000
So this is like why you would use service side rendering over client side, over the defaults.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:45.000
You don't want to blast your users with a million rows of data and put all that network bandwidth and break somebody's browser.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:47.000
So here's a million rows.

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:53.000
Pagination is still fairly fast, fast enough.

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:58.000
Search filtering is still very fast.

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:05.000
This is all, these 1 million rows are all in memory in this other server that I have.

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:08.000
So it's not on my laptop.

01:01:08.000 --> 01:01:11.000
I'm doing all the searching, sorting.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:16.000
Sorting kind of lags a bit, but still, you can see, not too bad.

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:18.000
As you probably know, this comes up a lot.

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:22.000
How do I deliver to my user a big table?

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:25.000
But I know there's no link to this yet.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:35.000
So if I wanted, imagine someone's watching this in the future, the recording of it, where is this example going to live to learn more about?

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:42.000
I have no idea yet, but hopefully it will be possible to find it from the websites.

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:48.000
It'll be a pretty, it should be a pretty important feature.

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:51.000
So I'll make sure you can find it.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:57.000
And for what it's worth, I recall the table contest, or maybe it was the Shiny contest if I'm confusing things.

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:02.000
I think it had a couple examples of kind of server-side with like pagination.

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:15.000
Yeah, there's one really awesome example from, I can't remember the name, but they basically implemented server-side data processing in Reactable, even when it wasn't possible.

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:18.000
So it was technically possible, kind of possible for it, but they did it.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:24.000
And the interesting thing about that was that it was using data that was not in memory.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:26.000
It wasn't like a SQLite database.

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:30.000
And you could also like pull data from a third-party API.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:32.000
And that will also be eventually possible.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:42.000
You can, you will be able to write your own custom backends to hook it up, hook up Reactable to like Postgres or SQLite database or some third-party API.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:50.000
But coming down the line, it's probably not going to be available immediately.

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:52.000
That's an awesome example.

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:55.000
That was a really cool table contest submission.

